02 Mar 2010 14:33






Minor nitpick from me - "titanium alloy polymer" is one buzzword too many. Metals and metal alloys do not form polymer chains. It's not unheard of for a polymer or other complex organic molecule to incorporate one or more metallic atoms, but this also does not grant them metallic properties. Also, "malleable" refers to an ability to be plastically (i.e. permanently) deformed, which would cause rapid fatigue of any structure (how many times can you bend a paperclip back and forth before it breaks?).

My suggestion would be to make the extra skeleton out of carbon nanofibers, since those are not only highly durable but also capable of acting as conductors or semiconductors, thus increasing the plausibility of both neural control and autonomous action. If you want to keep it metallic, then try something like a "novel titanium-based superalloy". Also, replace "malleable" with "elastic".





